<FIRST>u a AM-SuperCelebration 1stLd-Writethru a0791 01-22 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Celebration, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0791,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Revels In 49er Super Bowl Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 1st graf to UPDATE with arrests, road
closings. Subs penultimate graf with two grafs to UPDATE with comment from
cable company affected by video pirates. A version moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horns blared, fireworks lighted the sky and
strangers kissed in the streets Sunday night as fans celebrating the
San Francisco 49ers Super Bowl victory turned the town into an
impromptu open-air party.
   Authorities closed several streets and Highway 480 near the
Embarcadero because of crowds. Police reported numerous arrests,
most for public drunkenness, but did not have exact figures.
   Roman candles rocketed aloft as fans in the largely Hispanic
Mission District erupted into the streets to celebrate the 20-16
last-minute victory over the Cincinnati Bengals.
   ``We stomped them like bugs in a barn,'' said William Bernhard,
21, from his post on a jammed street corner. ``For the last five
minutes, it was like having an electric eel attached to your spine.''
   ``I feel great,'' said Manuel Anaya, 20, of San Francisco as he
jumped up and down on a crowded sidewalk, waving a 6-foot-long 49ers
banner. ``I knew it all the way. I never gave up, I never gave up.''
   A man leaned from an apartment window overlooking Mission Street,
and played a trombone.
   ``We expect the unusual right now,'' said Officer Stephanie
Thorne at the Mission District police station. ``Cars driving by
with their boom boxes, honking their horns. They're going pretty
good out there.''
   Additional officers were on duty for the evening, Thorne said,
although she couldn't say how many.
   At the jammed Mad Hatter sports bar, fans leaped into the air,
roaring, slapping high fives and wagging fingers at the television
screen.
   At Perry's, a bar, host Rob Hunter said the atmosphere has been
``insane'' all day.
   ``They've been going crazy ...,'' Hunter said. ``We knew we were
going to win it.''
   ``You can't walk on the street, you can't get in the door,'' he
said. ``That's what's going on. We had fire trucks, horses and
police blowing their sirens. It was great. Now they're blocking off
the street.''
   At a Redwood City bar-restaurant called Clark's, which is owned
by former 49ers wide receiver Dwight Clark, the crowd ``went crazy''
when 49er quarterback Joe Montana was shown on the post-game show
wearing a hat advertising the tavern, said hostess Pameaux Hudson.
   ``We had people on top of people and people on each other's laps,
sitting, standing, leaning,'' she said.
   Elsewhere, the broadcast of the game was interrupted for fans in
at least two parts of the country.
   In Los Angeles, the audio portion of a cable television broadcast
was disrupted for a few seconds with music from ``The Jetsons''
cartoon and an anti-Semitic slur.
   ``First there was music from `The Jetsons' cartoon show. Then
someone said something about Century Cable and `there's too many
(expletive deleted) Jews in this industry,''' said Doug Debber, a
viewer in Santa Monica.
   The interruption occurred about 3:15 p.m. when an audio signal
invaded Century's cable system, affecting viewers in West Los
Angeles, Santa Monica and Beverly Hills, a company official said.
   ``I'm baffled at how it was done and I'm shocked and outraged at
the statements that were made,'' said Bill Rosendahl, vice president
of Century Southwest Cable Television in Santa Monica.
   In eastern Ohio and the northern panhandle of West Virginia,
viewers of WTOV television missed much of the second quarter.
Technical problems put the station off the air for about 25 minutes,
a station worker said. The station serves a market of 154,000
households.
</TEXT>
