<HEAD>Three Held In Connection With Arson Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with third arrest. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `Survivors of...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third people were arrested and a fourth
person surrendered to police Saturday in connection with a predawn
arson fire that killed six people from four generations of a family,
police said.
   A 17-year-old boy and a 22-year-old man were arrested Saturday
within a few blocks of the house that was heavily damaged by fire
early Friday morning. Another 17-year-old boy surrendered to police
Saturday evening, said police spokesman Sgt. Gregory Mills.
   A 32-year-old man was arrested late Saturday evening, police said.
   No charges were immediately filed against the four, who were held
in the Jackson County Jail, police said.
   Survivors of the fire said a feud with a man who allegedly ran a
nearby drug house may have been the motive for the arson.
   The fire was discovered at 2:45 a.m. Friday by a man inside the
house who went to investigate the sound of breaking glass in the
first-floor living room, Mills said. The fire spread quickly up the
stairs to the second floor, where all six victims were found in
their bedrooms.
   Gasoline was used to start the blaze, Mills said. A nearly empty
five-gallon gasoline can was found near the broken window.
   Preliminary reports said the six victims, who represented four
generations of the family, died of smoke inhalation.
   The victims were identified as Trisha Phillips, 19; her baby,
Mark Sanders Jr., 6 months; Jason Addison, 2; Courtney Addison, 2;
Velma Coleman, 76, and Nola Phillips, 59.
   Two other occupants of the 2{-story frame house were
hospitalized. Four other people fled without serious injury.
   ``They lost their lives for nothing, over something that don't
really make no sense,'' said Mark Sanders, the father of the infant.
   Police had staked out the neighborhood Thursday after getting
``numerous complaints about drug activity,'' said Capt. James Nunn.
Several people were arrested on outstanding warrants after they left
a house in the block, he said.
</TEXT>
