<HEAD>Helicopter Crash Report Blames Pilot Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of a minesweeping helicopter off
the Golden Gate that killed eight crewmen was the result of pilot
error, according to a Navy investigation.
   The investigation found that mechanical error was not a factor in
the July 18 accident, despite earlier accidents involving models of
the Sea Dragon MH-53E three-engine helicopter, the San Francisco
Chronicle reported Saturday.
   The models have been involved in five accidents that cost at
least five lives. Three lawsuits stemming from these accidents have
been filed in California against the aircraft's manufacturer,
Sikorsky Aircraft Division of United Technologies Corp. in
Connecticut.
   The Navy investigation said salvage operators were able to
recover 95 percent of the helicopter. However, only six of the eight
crewmen were found. All eight died in the crash, which was eight
miles west of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
