<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-East-West Bjt   01-22 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West, Bjt,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accord Fosters Disarmament Hopes, Stirs Unrest in Alliances</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The document on human rights and security
35 nations approved in Vienna this month has narrowed the gap
between East and West but widened some fissures in their alliances.
   Both superpowers praise the agreement, which promises broader
individual freedoms and provides for new arms talks, as a herald of
future disarmament successes.
   The ultimate success of the 27-month conference that produced the
document, however, has stirred unrest within the blocs led by
Washington and Moscow.
   European members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization show
increasing resistance to U.S. views of how disarmament should
proceed on their continent.
   Warsaw Pact allies of the Soviet Union demonstrate markedly
different degrees of commitment to the human rights protections
spelled out in the Vienna accord.
   Whether the internal divisions will develop into disabling rifts
will depend in large part on the superpower leaders.
   President Bush is expected to continue Reagan administration
policies on disarmament, but mounting pressure from Europe could
produce an approach more receptive to the Kremlin.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program has met
resistance at home and in some nations of the Soviet bloc. At the
moment, Gorbachev desperately needs to cut arms spending as a way of
stabilizing the economy and improving the living standard.
   Western allies are aware of the pressure he faces and of the
serious consequences for arms control if Gorbachev's conservative
opponents gain the upper hand.
   U.S. diplomats concede the Vienna conference succeeded primarily
because of the Soviet reforms.
   Earlier this month, the State Department said release of
political prisoners, easing of emigration and more tolerant policies
on free speech and religious practice changed the American position
on the Soviet proposal for a 1991 human rights conference in Moscow.
   Agreement on a final document in Vienna was delayed because
Western nations objected to holding such a meeting in Moscow. The
conference was one of several since 1975, when the United States,
Canada and all European nations except Albania signed the Helsinki
agreements on European security and cooperation.
   The Vienna statement approved Jan. 15 proclaims the right of all
citizens to assemble, speak their minds, travel, emigrate and
monitor compliance of their governments.
   It sets ambitious goals for better trade relations and
environmental protection and mandates new negotiations on reducing
conventional military forces in Europe, to begin March 9 in Vienna.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze of the Soviet Union, in
Vienna for the closing session, described the agreement as the
result of commitment and compromise.
   He said the Kremlin would disclose the numbers of its soldiers
and armaments in Europe before the new talks begin. Arguments and
secrecy surrounding the relative strength of forces have hamstrung
existing negotiations that began 15 years ago.
   Asked why he was so confident the new forum would avoid the
pitfalls of the old, Shevardnadze said the alliances were under
increasing pressure to improve the international climate.
   ``It's something our peoples want and their governments, if they
are true governments, should express the will of the people,'' he
told reporters.
   In his speech to the conference, Shevardnadze said the Kremlin
would remove some short-range nuclear weapons from Eastern Europe
and asked NATO to negotiate withdrawal of the remaining
European-based missiles with ranges of 300 miles or less.
   All missiles of intermediate range are being withdrawn and
dismantled under an accord signed in Washington in December 1987,
and negotiators report good progress on a pact to cut stockpiles of
long-range weapons.
   Washington has said repeatedly it does not want to give up
short-range nuclear arms until a Soviet advantage in conventional
forces is reduced.
   ``There's not going to be anything left except the short-range,''
a senior U.S. diplomat said. ``If we want to keep the flexible
response doctrine credible, I don't see any way we can negotiate
these in the foreseeable future.''
   That NATO doctrine holds that the West must retain its nuclear
option until the Soviet advantage in troops, tanks, artillery and
other conventional weapons is reduced.
   West Germany and other NATO members, however, have been chafing
under that and other constraints on the pace of disarmament.
   Stephen Ledogar, the U.S. ambassador to the forthcoming talks,
said Washington wants to see a Soviet reduction in conventional
forces first, but added: ``I'm not trying to suggest there is no
difference of opinion within the alliance.''
   Within the Warsaw Pact, the Soviet Union's planned pullouts are
popular with the masses but worrisome for some leaderships.
   Even more divisive is the question of human rights and the
varying degrees of willingness among the East-bloc allies to emulate
the Gorbachev policies of glasnost and perestroika.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Carol J. Williams has reported from Eastern
Europe and the Soviet Union for The Associated Press since 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890122-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-MideastPeace Bjt   01-22 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mideast Peace, Bjt,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europeans Step Up Middle East Peace Role</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As George Bush looks to the Middle East in
the first days of his presidency, he will find Soviet and European
leaders jostling to share the stage in the peace process that once
seemed an American monopoly.
   The United States remains the region's most important outside
power. But it no longer holds the solo role of matchmaker it played
in the 1979 Egyptian-Israeli treaty.
   ``I believe that Europe is making, can make and will make a
considerable contribution ... toward this Middle East peace
settlement,'' Lord Plumb, President of the European Parliament, said
in Jordan this month.
   The Europeans have played a path-finding role that often has
complimented American actions _ as well as channeling them.
   Their contacts with the Palestine Liberation Organization helped
both legitimize the organization and prod it toward more moderate
positions that opened the way for a dialogue with Washington.
   European calls for Israeli compromise have underscored quieter
U.S. pressure on the Jewish state.
   Sweden was a crucial mediator late last year to draw the United
States back into contact with the PLO after a 13-year U.S. boycott.
   Spain's embassy in Tunis hosted clandestine meetings to help pave
the way for those talks.
   Its foreign minister, delegated by the 12-nation European
Community, visited Israeli leaders this month and urged them to
respond to PLO peace efforts.
   Soviet officials pressured their leftist allies in the PLO to
accept Israel, renounce terrorism and endorse U.N. peace
resolutions, setting the stage for the U.S.-PLO dialogue.
   Both the Soviet Union and China have improved relations with
Israel, partly in expectation of a role in Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   European parliamentarians and ministers have paraded through the
Holy Land on political pilgrimages, lecturing irritated Israeli
leaders on the need to compromise.
   Italian, Spanish, Greek, British, Scandinavian and East European
leaders have met PLO chief Yasser Arafat to encourage the PLO's
shift from the gun to the conference table. France upgraded the PLO
mission in Paris to a ``general delegation'' _ a step short of
diplomatic recognition.
   The barrage of activity led Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
to accuse the European Community on Jan.13 of a ``love affair'' with
the PLO.
   He insisted the community ``cannot bring us closer to the PLO.
That depends only on us. They have no right to impose solutions or
to apply economic pressure.''
   America's long boycott of the PLO eventually achieved a key aim.
The organization last month embraced the moderate stands Washington
had demanded to help sow the seeds of a possible peace settlement.
   But the U.S. isolation of the PLO worked both ways.
   Its repeated efforts to find an alternative to the PLO were all
but demolished by the 13-month-old Palestinian uprising, which
evoked a storm of pro-PLO sentiment in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   The policy also caused popular hostility to American policy
throughout the Arab world, whose governments unanimously insist the
PLO is central to any settlement.
   Washington was unable to get Shamir to agree on the U.S.-backed
concept of trading occupied Arab land for peace _ the heart of all
major Middle East peace efforts over the past 20 years.
   The United States largely stood by as Israeli troops invaded
Lebanon and bombed Beirut in 1982, then reneged on a promise to
protect Palestinian refugees after the PLO's withdrawal from Lebanon.
   Congress blocked a key arms deal for Jordan, considered the Arab
key to American Middle East peace plans, infuriating King Hussein.
   By 1984, Hussein said the United States had ruled itself out as a
sole peace mediator. Together with Arafat, he embraced a
Soviet-inspired call for the five permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council to oversee Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   That plan eventually won broad European support as frustrated
Arabs increasingly asked Western Europe to pressure the United
States to influence Israel.
   Europe responded, keeping an eye on its major economic interests
in the region and mindful of the perils of war between increasingly
well-armed rivals on its southern flank.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   John Rice, The Associated Press correspondent in
Amman, has covered Palestinian affairs for five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890122-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WarsawPact-Glance     01-22 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw Pact-Glance,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Europe At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East-West, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief review of the political, social and economic
policies of Warsaw Pact countries:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET UNION _ Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who gained power in March
1985, has pursued policies that enlarged personal freedoms, promoted
economic change, reduced involvement in such regional conflicts as
Afghanistan and took major steps in arms control. His domestic
reforms are endangered by conservatives in high places; ethnic
strife between Armenians and Azerbaijanis; and nationalist movements
in the Baltic states of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. Gorbachev
also faces opposition because living conditions are slow to improve
and conservatives see danger in disarmament.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POLAND _ Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's government has agreed to give
workers a greater voice in economic decisions by offering to
legalize Solidarity with some conditions. The concession seems born
of frustration over inability either to stop an economic slide or
inspire Poles to accept price increases and other means of financing
reform.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HUNGARY _ The Warsaw Pact pioneer in economic and social change
plans to open the first stock market in a communist country and has
set the stage for a multiparty political system. It has been the
most vocal of Moscow's allies in pressing for international
standards on human rights guarantees and has been tolerant of
protest and unofficial groups.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EAST GERMANY _ The 16 million Germans ruled by Erich Honecker
have one of the bloc's most industrially productive nations but have
not won the greater freedom championed by Gorbachev and instituted
in Hungary. Restrictions on emigration and travel have been eased
somewhat, but the Berlin Wall remains a symbol of repression and a
point of contention between East and West.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CZECHOSLOVAKIA _ Although it has the highest living standard of
the seven Warsaw Pact nations, Czechoslovakia takes one of the
hardest lines on dissent and has balked at many of Gorbachev's
political and economic reforms. Police attacks on demonstrators in
Prague this month have emphasized the different attitudes among
Soviet allies on free expression.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BULGARIA _ The nation Todor Zhivkov has led 34 years is known as
one of the Kremlin's most loyal followers but has been slow to
embrace change. Human rights abuses and police repression are
reported with increasing frequency as those advocating reform
challenge the leadership.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ROMANIA _ Nicolae Ceausescu runs the most repressive nation in
the Soviet bloc and his attempt to rid it of foreign debt also has
left Romania financially strapped. Food and power shortages have
further reduced a poor standard of living. Hesitant attempts at
public disagreement with the ``The Chosen One,'' as Ceausescu is
called, have met harsh response. Romania said it would refuse to
honor any provisions of the Vienna document it considered intrusive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
