<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--FalsePoll     01-22 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--False Poll,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Published False Results On Popularity Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magazine falsely reported results of a
popularity poll to say that Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz had
the highest score, state radio said.
   The latest edition of the popular independent weekly Reform said
Grosz topped the list of its ``The Year's Reform Man'' survey with
22.9 percent of nearly 5,000 votes received.
   Pal Emoed, a Reform editorial board member, told the radio late
Saturday that ``not even'' 500 votes had arrived in the magazine
office. He told the radio that of those votes, Grosz finished second
to Imre Pozsgay, a minister of state and leading reformer.
   Emoed gave no figures and did not say who was responsible for
publishing the allegedly false results.
   The public admission of error was extremely unusual in a
Communist country, even in Hungary, where the media have become
increasingly open over the past year.
</TEXT>
