<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     01-22 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scowcroft: U.S. Takes Wait and See Stance on Talks With Arafat</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House national security adviser Brent
Scowcroft said Sunday it would be ``premature'' to arrange a
high-level Bush administration meeting with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat until Arafat's intentions are more clearly known.
   Scowcroft's comments came amid Arab press reports that spoke of
intensifying Arab efforts to arrange a meeting between Arafat,
chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and Secretary of
State-designate James A. Baker III.
   ``We already have established discussions with Chairman Arafat,
and it seems to me we ought to explore and probe what he sees as the
evolution of this,'' Scowcroft said on ABC-TV's ``This Week With
David Brinkley.''
   He noted that the United States decided to resume contacts with
the PLO because Arafat came around to the U.S. view on recognizing
Israel's right to exist.
   ``What has happened in our changed policy toward Arafat is not a
new United States initiative,'' Scowcroft said. ``The chairman
could've had that at any time since 1975. Then he decided to do what
he finally did. Now, it seems to me, we find out what it is he has
in mind.''
   Asked specifically about the desirability of a meeting between
Baker and Arafat, Scowcroft said: ``I think it would be premature to
meet at such a high level until we have a better indication of where
Mr. Arafat may be going.''
   Abu Dhabi's state-run daily newspaper Al-Ittihad said Sunday that
Egypt has extended an invitation to Baker to visit the Middle East
to pave the way for an international peace conference.
   Quoting unidentified sources in Cairo, the newspaper said Egypt's
``intensive current efforts with Washington are aimed at arranging a
meeting between Arafat and Baker during that tour.''
   The Saudi Arabian newspaper Al-Madina also quoted unnamed sources
as saying consultations were under way to prepare an Arafat-Baker
meeting in Tunis in mid-February.
   The Reagan administration broke a 13-year ban on U.S. talks with
the PLO last month. Secretary of State George P. Shultz said the
decision was based on a public statement by Arafat renouncing
terrorism in all forms and accepting Israel's right to exist.
   The State Department revealed last week that a second, more
informal ``contact'' with the PLO had been made in Tunis on Jan. 17.
The department also released a partial transcript of a tape
recording in which Arafat vowed to shoot anyone who tried to stem
Palestinian unrest on the Israeli-held West Bank.
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy said last month
that talks with the PLO would be suspended if Arafat reneged on his
renunciation of terrorism.
   On another issue, Scowcroft said suspected poison gas plants in
Libya and Iraq pose a very serious problem, but he declined to say
whether the Bush administration would endorse use of force to knock
them out.
   ``They are a terrible problem. And it is a problem akin in its
scope to that of nuclear proliferation, because these weapons _
especially in city attacks, anti-population attacks _ can be every
bit as devastating as nuclear weapons,'' he said.
   Scowcroft noted that ``they are much harder to control, because
the plants to produce them are in many cases like pharmaceutical
plants, like insecticide plants.''
   He was questioned about whether it would be more serious to use
force against such chemical weapons plants or to let them go into
production.
   ``Sometimes one has to make a choice between undesirable
alternatives,'' Scowcroft replied.
   But he added: ``I'm not about to make that choice now.''
</TEXT>
