<HEAD>Prominent GOP Fund-Raiser Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buckley Morris Byers, deputy chairman of the
Republican National Finance Committee, died Friday at Georgetown
University Hospital after suffering a stroke. He was 72.
   Byers, president of Byers-McManus Associates Inc., a Washington
consulting firm, had served as deputy chairman of the GOP
fund-raising committee since 1976.
   A native of suburban Pittsburgh, Byers in 1964 was treasurer for
the campaign of Republican Sen. Hugh Scott of Pennsylvania.
   He came to Washington in 1961 as a vice president for Blaw-Knox
Co., a steel company. He previously had served as president of the
A.M. Byers Steel Co., which was founded by his grandfather.
   Byers was a graduated of Yale University and served in the Navy
in World War II.
   A memorial service was scheduled for 3 p.m. Monday in Washington
at the Church of the Immaculate Conception. Internment will be
Tuesday at the Allegheny Cemetery in Pittsburgh.
