<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Cardinals     01-22 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Cardinals,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Says It Will Maintain Age Limit for Conclave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Vatican official announced that Pope
John Paul II will retain a rule barring elderly cardinals from
electing new popes, a source said Sunday. The rule has reportedly
caused dissension among cardinals.
   The Vatican source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Monsignor Agnelo Rossi, dean of the College of Cardinals, said in a
letter to the cardinals the pope is keeping the rule enacted by his
predecessor, Paul VI.
   The Italian news agency ANSA, in a report on the letter, said
Rossi noted at recent meetings of cardinals that there has been open
criticism about the rule, which bars cardinals 80 years and older
from voting for new popes.
   Other news reports Sunday said Rossi's announcement came in
response to a letter to the pope signed by 10 cardinals asking for a
change in the rule.
   However, several of the 10 cardinals named in the reports denied
signing such a letter. Such a letter would be unusual since it would
be a formal display of dissent at the top of the church hierarchy.
   After the pontiff, cardinals come next in the hierarchy of the
Roman Catholic Church. There are currently 156 cardinals, of whom
119 are under 80.
   In 1970, Pope Paul VI withdrew from cardinals 80 years or older
the right to elect popes and hold Vatican office. He hoped to
rejuvenate the Roman Curia _the central offices of the Catholic
Church _ and the secret conclaves of cardinals that elect the pope
to replace a deceased one.
   The change has been a source of criticism since by some cardinals.
   The Italian news agency Adn Kronos reported Saturday that 10
cardinals had signed a letter asking for a change in the law, and
the Milan daily Corriere della Sera said it had confirmed the report.
   However, ANSA on Sunday said it contacted four of the cardinals
named by the agency and they denied signing any such letter.
   One of the four cited by ANSA, Cardinal Corrado Bafile, told The
Associated Press he had not signed a letter about the age limit. He
said that the reports ``are not true, at least on this point.'' He
would not elaborate.
   Cardinal Silvio Oddi was quoted as saying in Sunday's La
Repubblica newspaper that he didn't sign any such letter because
``no one asked me to. But, sincerely, I would have signed it without
hesitation.''
   He was further quoted as saying: ``If a person is fully lucid and
capable of reason why forbid him from voting?''
</TEXT>
