<FIRST>r a AM-SupremacistMarch     01-22 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Supremacist March,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say March Control Went Generally Well, But Plan Inquiries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials plan to investigate police actions
during a white supremacist march that drew bricks and bottles from
angry counterdemonstrators, but the city's top policeman believes
there were no major problems.
   The city response to Saturday's march by a handful of Nationalist
Movement followers ``was as good as we could make it,'' said George
Napper, Atlanta's commissioner of public safety.
   But he said some allegations would be looked into, including
reports of officers clubbing and arresting uninvolved spectators
while trying to control the angry crowds.
   ``Obviously, there were some incidents, but I thought by and
large we avoided anything major. This city has a legacy to work
things out. ... I think that's why we haven't had the kind of
situations that took place in Miami,'' he said referring to last
week's riots there.
   Police reported 42 arrests in the confrontation between the
half-dozen white supremacist marchers and the hundreds of
counterdemonstrators. Hospital officials said they treated 13
people, including police officers, members of the Georgia Army
National Guard and counterdemonstrators, for minor injuries.
   Atlanta was quiet Sunday. Parts of the march route were still
littered with bricks, boards, broken bottles, rocks and chunks of
concrete hurled at the marchers and the police and National Guard
members protecting them.
   In all, an estimated 2,000 National Guard members and state and
local police were mobilized in what appeared at first to be a
striking case of overkill.
   But Atlanta, which is heavily black, houses several colleges and
universities and has a sizable counterculture community _ all
potential sources of participants for countering a white supremacist
march.
   Counterdemonstrators and bystanders, estimated at between 1,000
and 3,000, overwhelmed police lines along parts of the route,
charged toward the marchers and hurled objects.
   ``The city invited this kind of thing'' by issuing the white
supremacists a march permit, charged Dianne Mathiowetz, a member of
the Ad Hoc Committee Against the Klan.
   Michele Allen, another counterdemonstrator, said the
rock-throwers ``are just as bad as the Klan. People have to stand up
to the Klan, but there has to be some peaceful way. This is a war
zone.''
   Mississippi lawyer Richard Barrett, who heads the Nationalist
Movement, and his handful of followers sang and shouted anti-Martin
Luther King slogans along the route of about two miles.
   Barrett attempted the march on the eve of last July's Democratic
National Convention, but the city canceled his permit when hundreds
of counterdemonstrators massed at the Capitol and police feared
violence.
   He said Saturday's march was a restaging of the earlier effort as
well as a repudiation of King, whom he called a tyrant and a sexual
pervert, and of the national holiday honoring the slain civil rights
leader.
   Barrett declined to say if he would try to march again in
Atlanta. ``I have just begun to fight,'' he said.
   After the march, Napper went to Five Points, Atlanta's central
downtown intersection, where at least 1,000 mostly black youths
remained assembled, watched by scores of police on horseback or in
riot control gear.
   Napper, who like most of Atlanta's top law enforcement officials
is black, was pelted with questions and insults asking why Barrett's
group was allowed to march and was given protection.
   ``You protect the Klan but you won't protect us. You ain't my
commissioner,'' one woman screamed. ``You're protecting people who
will lynch my grandchildren,'' yelled another.
   Napper, who broke out of the crowd with police help, said: ``They
are entitled to protection. It's not always easy.''
</TEXT>
