<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-ChemicalWeapons 1stLd-Writethru   01-22 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Chemical Weapons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Accused of Delivering Equipment For Chemical Arms to Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Libyan Chemicals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with three grafs to clarify German law. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs, ``The documents ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities suspect a West German
company shipped equipment to Iraq that could be used to make
chemical weapons, a prosecutor said Sunday.
   Darmstadt prosecutor Thomas Brand said documents seized from
offices of the Preussag company of Hanover indicate it shipped
containers and other equipment to Iraq that ``with relative
certainty, could have been used in the production of chemical
weapons.'' Brand spoke in an interview broadcast by Hamburg-based
Spiegel TV network.
   It is not against West German law to ship Iraq industrial goods.
The legal issue is whether the company knew the consignments would
be used to produce chemical weapons.
   The documents, some seized in 1987, also indicate the company
delivered specialized equipment to Iraq that could be used to
produce poison gas shells and bombs, he said.
   No charges have been filed, Brand said.
   Preussag's administrative offices in Hanover and Darmstadt were
closed Sunday, and company officials could not be reached for
comment.
   Brand's office is investigating three other West German companies
in connection with sales to Iraq. The prosecutor has jurisdiction in
the case because Preussag owns a subsidiary near southern Darmstadt.
   Brand last week named two of the companies, Karl Kolb GmbH and
Co. and the now-defunct Pilot Plant company. He refused to name the
third company under investigation.
   Brand said his allegations are based on ``preliminary
evaluations'' and investigations are continuing to determine whether
export laws have been broken.
   Investigators are focusing on a West German law that requires an
export license to ship arms, hazardous substances or components that
can be used to produce them. In addition, a wide-ranging law forbids
such exports to areas of conflict.
   Other news reports have linked West German technicians and
scientists to production of biological weapons in Iraq.
   The West German government has said it has indications such a
plant may operate in Iraq but no evidence of German participation.
   Brand's comments came as controversy continued over alleged
involvement by West German companies in such sales to Iraq and Libya.
   At least two West German companies are under criminal
investigation in connection with a suspected Libyan chemical weapons
factory, and investigators are investigating a Munich-based company
suspected of helping Libya develop the capability to refuel
warplanes in flight.
   U.S. officials contend the Libyan factory in Rabta, south of
Tripoli, is designed to produce poison gas. Libya says the facility
will manufacture pharmaceuticals.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Sunday that U.S. officials
received a crucial clue about the Rabta plant's operations after the
deaths of wild dogs in the Libyan desert.
   The newspaper said a toxic spill of chemical wastes at the site
last August apparently killed the dogs and that panicked Libyans
breached security by using international phone lines to call a
German firm helping them build the plant.
   Allegations that West German companies were involved in the
Middle East sales and the Libyan plant have stunned and embarrassed
the West German government and dominated news media here for three
weeks.
   On Sunday, the Hamburg-based Bild am Sonntag newspaper reported
that government officials, furious over the way the investigation
has been handled, are demanding the resignation of West Germany's
intelligence chief.
   Chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost called the report ``pure
speculation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890122-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SorryThief     01-22 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sorry Thief,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guilty Conscience Prompts Apology, Return Of Stolen Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burglars had struck Dave Pastorek's gas
station twice in three days, making off with a total of more than
$3,000.
   Then on Friday, a big manila envelope arrived in the mail and
Pastorek figured it was more bad news, maybe from his lawyer or
accountant.
   Inside, a note read:
   ``I am sorry.
   ``I drank too much and broke into your station on a dare.
   ``I am sorry.''
   Along with the note, he found $167 in cash, and checks and credit
card receipts worth about $1,600 _ everything that had been stolen
from the station one week earlier.
   ``I about died,'' said Pastorek, 30. ``We figure his conscience
was bothering him, and he probably wasn't able to sleep for four or
five nights.''
   Now, he said, he's waiting for the burglar who hit Jan. 16 to get
a case of the guilts. That one got away with about $1,400 in
receipts.
   ``If the first guy did it on a dare, I'm wondering if maybe the
second guy was the one who dared him. Maybe after he saw it could be
done, he decided to try it himself,'' Pastorek said.
   Coincidentally, the city kicked off an honesty campaign last
week, directed by the Columbus Commission on Ethics and Values.
   The head of the commission is Jeb Stuart Magruder, a Watergate
conspirator who is now a Presbyterian minister.
</TEXT>
