<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-RedCross     01-22 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Red Cross,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Workers Return to Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four International Red Cross workers returned to
Beirut on Sunday, just one month after death threats and a
kidnapping prompted the humanitarian organization to scrap its
operations in Lebanon.
   Juergen Bischoff, a spokesman for the Switzerland-based
International Committee of the Red Cross, confirmed the arrival of
the workers but declined to give details.
   ``A statement will probably be issued tomorrow in Beirut or in
Geneva,'' he said.
   The International Red Cross announced Dec. 20 that ``serious
threats had been made against its delegates in Lebanon, placing
their lives in acute danger.''
   The decision came four days after kidnappers in Lebanon released
Red Cross official Peter Winkler, who had been held hostage for more
than a month.
   The group behind the kidnapping and a series of death threats
never has been clearly identified. Swiss authorities said the
captors were an otherwise unknown dissident Palestinian group called
Organization of the Socialist Revolution.
   Senior Red Cross officials have been traveling to various Middle
East capitals during the past month in an apparent effort to obtain
guarantees from all parties that they could resume operations
without having to fear violence.
   Fifteen Western foreigners are missing in Lebanon, including nine
Americans, most of them believed held by Shiites loyal to Iran.
   Longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
