<FIRST>r p AM-LouisianaElection     01-22 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Election,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klansman Says Election Signals Change In Voter Sentiment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ku Klux Klansman David Duke said his
top finish in a primary election for state representative signals
renewed voter interest in white supremacy.
   Duke, former imperial wizard of the Knights of the Ku Klux Klan,
led a field of seven candidates in Saturday's primary election for a
vacant state House seat representing a suburban district that is 99
percent white. Duke received 33 percent of the vote and will face
second-place finisher John Treen in a Feb. 18 runoff. Treen had 19
percent of the vote.
   ``I think the people knew that by my past involvement (with the
Klan), people know that I say what I really believe,'' Duke said
after Saturday's vote. ``The Klan is far behind me, but the effort
for equal rights for everybody is ahead of me.
   ``I think when I win this race you'll find candidates across the
state and across the country begin to talk about the issues I'm
raising. I think this is the beginning of a change in this country.''
   Duke left the Klan in 1980 after being accused of trying to sell
top-secret membership lists and set up the National Association for
the Advancement of White People. He calls himself a white civil
rights worker.
   Louisiana's open primary system places all candidates on the same
ballot, regardless of party affiliation. If none receives a
majority, there is a runoff election between the top two
vote-getters.
   Saturday's vote in Jefferson Parish represented a 54 percent
turnout of registered voters.
   Duke, 38, ran as a Republican with a campaign platform including
proposed welfare revisions aimed at reducing black births. He said
Saturday that he fully expected the platform to carry him into the
Legislature in February.
   ``I think most people know I am trying to help them,'' he said.
``I think those (racial) issues are hurting our community's economy,
increasing crime....''
   Treen, 68, also a Republican and brother of former Louisiana Gov.
David Treen, said the outcome was due to a solid voting bloc for
Duke and a large field of candidates.
   He disagreed with Duke's claim that the result showed racial
overtones.
   ``I don't think that's true at all. I don't think the people are
trying to send a message to anybody,'' Treen said. ``There were a
number of fine candidates in this race. The vote was split in so
many directions that his lead is not indicative of the direction or
the attitudes of the voters of Jefferson Parish.''
   Treen, who has been endorsed by several local politicians, said
other candidates in the race have committed their support to him in
the runoff.
   Treen is a construction contractor. Duke describes himself as a
professional writer who contributes articles on history and other
subjects to periodicals under a pseudonym, which he said avoids
problems with publication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
