<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     01-22 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Questions Tougher Measures As Palestinians Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet on Sunday debated a policy that
gives troops greater freedom to shoot at Palestinian protesters, and
both Palestinians and Israelis rejected a new peace plan for the
occupied lands.
   In the occupied territories, most shopkeepers closed stores to
observe a strike called by the Moslem fundamentalist Hamas movement,
and the army imposed curfews that confined about 180,000 Arabs to
their homes in several Gaza Strip refugee camps.
   Arab news reports said six Palestinian protesters were shot and
wounded in clashes with soldiers in the occupied Gaza Strip and West
Bank. The army could not confirm the casualties but reported two
other woundings.
   At the weekly Cabinet meeting, Energy Minister Moshe Shahal of
the center-left Labor Party criticized the Defense Ministry's
decision to liberalize orders for opening fire on Palestinian
protesters.
   The new rules allow officers and soldiers with special training
to shoot plastic bullets at Arabs who throw stones and set up
roadblocks. Previously, only officers were allowed to fire the
plastic bullets, and only in life-threatening situations.
   ``I think the issue is worth checking,'' Shahal told Israel radio
before the Cabinet meeting, adding that the new orders were
``possibly illegal.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, also of Labor, and other
ministers lashed out at Shahal's criticism, the radio said.
   ``We have an emergency situation ... and have to do everything
possible to quell the riots,'' Cabinet Minister Ehud Olmert of the
right-wing Likud Bloc said on Israel Radio.
   Israel radio said Justice Ministry lawyers planned to discuss the
issue with military attorneys later this week.
   Speaking on Israel television after the Cabinet meeting, Labor
leader and Finance Minister Shimon Peres defended the use of plastic
bullets, which have been blamed for at least 40 deaths.
   ``Why do we use plastic bullets? Not because it gives us great
pleasure, but because regular bullets cause more deaths,'' he said.
   At least 367 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have died in the
uprising that began Dec. 8, 1987.
   The Association for Civil Rights in Israel has appealed to the
Supreme Court to review and examine the use of plastic bullets,
Israel's Army Radio said.
   According to the independent Hadashot newspaper, the army is
about to introduce a new type of rubber bullet more effective in
dispersing crowds but incapable of penetrating the skin. A military
spokesman refused comment.
   Meanwhile, both Palestinians and Israelis rejected an unofficial
peace proposal put forth Thursday by Rabin, who offered free
elections in the territories in exchange for a cease-fire in the
uprising, peace talks and eventually a confederation between the
occupied lands and Israel or Jordan.
   Bethelehem's Palestinian mayor, Elias Freij told Israel radio the
plan ``will lead nowhere.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization rejected Rabin's plan
Friday.
   The leftist Peace Now movement said the proposal could be viewed
as serious only if accompanied by cancellation of harsh army
policies and the release of detained Arab leaders.
   Within Rabin's own left-leaning Labor, Communications Minister
Gad Yaacobi said that he accepts the plan just ``as an interim
stage, not as a final settlement.''
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, on a two-day visit, called
for direct negotiations with Palestinians to ensure ``peace,
stability and security in the region.''
   ``Peace can only come about only via direct negotiations between
the parties directly involved, and that means mutual, reciprocal
recognition,'' Dumas said after meetings with President Chaim
Herzog, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Peres.
   In the Gaza Strip, assailants presumed to be Palestinians hurled
two firebombs at a bus full of Arab workers breaking a general
strike by reporting to jobs in Israel. The workers fled the burning
bus and no one was injured, an Arab reporter said.
   Also Sunday, a military court in Lod, sentenced three
Palestinians to prison terms of at least 20 years for attacks on
Israel.
   One, a member of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah faction, guided the
suicide driver of last October's car bomb that killed eight Israeli
soldiers in southern Lebanon.
</TEXT>
