<FIRST>u i AM-HolocaustHero 1stLd-Writethru a0683 01-22 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holocaust Hero, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Foreign Minister Remembers Holocaust; Urges Talks With Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with Dumas calling for direct
talks between Israel and Palestinians; picks 4th graf `Dumas then...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas of France planted
a tree at a Holocaust memorial Sunday in honor of his father, a
French resistance leader who saved Jews during World War II before
the Nazis executed him.
   Dumas, in Israel for a two-day visit, also called on Israeli
leaders to hold direct talks with Palestinians, without specifically
mentioning the PLO.
   ``Peace can only come about only via direct negotiations between
the parties directly involved, and that means mutual, reciprocal
recognition,'' Dumas told a news conference after meeting with
President Chaim Herzog, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Finance
Minister Shimon Peres.
   Speaking on Israel television, Peres said Israel is prepared to
meet with Palestinian leaders from the occupied territories, but
would not consider meeting with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which he said engages in ``terror and violence.''
   ``We don't reject a people or a nation, but an organization,''
Peres said.
   Accompanied by Simone Nathan-Asher, one of the French Jews whom
his father, Georges Dumas, saved, the foreign minister laid a wreath
the Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial's eternal flame kept alight in
memory of the 6 million Jews who were killed by the Nazis.
   Dumas then walked through the memorial gardens to a special park
dedicated to those non-Jews who risked their lives to save Jews. He
planted the foot-high sapling, shoveled earth around it and watered
the small tree.
   ``When you are responsible for public affairs, as I am, the
memories you carry in your soul are always present,'' Dumas said.
   ``I thank you for suggesting this opportunity, in the name of my
father, and ... all those who displayed the necessary behavior,
inspired by a respect for individual rights and a love of liberty,''
he said.
   Dumas said his father Georges, as a member of the resistance,
helped warn Jews in the French town of Limoges of imminent raids,
hid them, and provided them with false documents so they could
escape.
   Among the people whom his father saved was a schoolgirl, Simone
Nathan-Asher, who survived by staying hidden in a monastary, he said.
   Ms. Nathan-Asher broke down in tears as she came forward to
express thanks to Dumas.
   Georges Dumas, a pilot during World War I, was executed by the
Nazis on March 26, 1944, after being identified as a resistance
leader.
</TEXT>
