<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-22 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms In Northwest And Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposite corners of the nation were wet Sunday with rain and snow
in the Northwest and wind and rain in the Southeast.
   Showers and thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain overnight
in Florida, and the rain continued into Sunday over parts of
Florida, southeastern Georgia and coastal South Carolina.
   Gale force wind accompanied the rain along Florida's northeastern
coast. Wind gusted to 47 mph at Daytona Beach during the afternoon
and to 63 mph at Titusville. Only minor damage was reported, the
National Weather Service said.
   In the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 2.14 inches of rain fell at
Daytona Beach.
   A cold front spread snow over parts of the Northwest, and a
winter storm warning was issued for southeastern and central
Montana, where up to 8 inches of snow was possible by Monday
morning. Wind gusts to 58 mph were reported at Casper, Wyo.
   Showers spread along the coast of Oregon and northern California.
   Afternoon temperatures remaining below freezing were confined to
Montana, North Dakota, Minnesota, upstate New York and northern New
England.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 3
degrees above zero at Gunnison, Colo., to 80 at Fort Lauderdale,
Fla. Sunday morning's low was 24 degrees below zero at Gunnison.
   For Monday, snow was forecast from Montana into northern Colorado
and western Nebraska. Scattered showers were forecast from the
California coast across much of Nevada. A few showers also were
forecast over south-central Texas.
   Highs never rising above freezing were predicted from the central
Rockies to northern Minnesota, and across northern Maine, including
highs only in the upper teens in North Dakota and eastern Montana;
in the 50s and 60s from the California coast through southern
Arizona to the upper Ohio Valley and the Southeast; and in the 70s
in southern Florida and the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas.
</TEXT>
