<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   01-22 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld - Writethru,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Arresteed At Martyr's Grave; Dubcek Offers Sympathy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-11, ``The protests...and dogs.'' with seven grafs
to UPDATE with Dubcek comments; picks up 12 pvs: On Jan. 16...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested up to 500 people
who tried to attend a vigil at the grave of a student who burned
himself to death to protest the 1968 Soviet-led invasion, activists
said Sunday.
   The protesters were arrested in the village of Vsetaty, 18 miles
from Prague and the hometown of Jan Palach, who killed himself in
Wencensclas Square in January 1969.
   Activist Petr Uhl said between 400 and 500 people who tried to
hold a vigil at the heavily guarded cemetery where Palach is buried
were arrested on Saturday. Police had blocked roads and interrogated
visitors on Saturday.
   The arrests bring to 800 the number of people held during a week
of anti-government protests, the biggest wave of unrest in the
Czechoslovakia in 20 years.
   A heavy police presence in Prague and Vsetaty, threats of
prosecution and the hundreds of arrests appeared to have stilled the
protests by Sunday.
   Uhl, a member of the Charter 77 activist group, said police
detained people Saturday who could not prove they were Vsetaty
residents. He said most were taken to a nearby state farm,
questioned, photographed and released.
   Uhl said two activists, Ludvik Marks of the independent youth
group Czech Children and Martin Litomirsky of the Democratic
Initiative, apparently had been detained overnight.
   Uhl also reported that Havel's lawyer had seen the jailed
activist on Friday. He said the activists could face charges with
penalities of up to three years in jail.
   The protests signal a growing frustration with the lack of social
and economic reforms similiar to those implemented by Mikhail
Gorbachev in the Soviet Union, said Alexander Dubcek, whose ``Prague
Spring'' reforms of Czechoslovakia were crushed by Soviet troops in
1968.
   Dubcek was ousted as former Communist Party chief in
Czechoslovakia by the Soviets in August 1968 after a fleeting
attempt to introduce many of the reforms now embraced by Gorbachev.
   Dubcek was interviewed by telephone by the Italian Communist
Party daily l'Unita, which carried a front-page story on Sunday. He
was asked to comment on the current wave of protests in
Czechoslovakia.
   ``There is a basic crisis that involves, above all, the young
people, the 20-year-old children of the Prague Spring ... who have
no future,'' Dubcek was quoted as saying.
   ``What young people are asking for is a rebirth of the type
underway in the Soviet Union, that involves even the party for the
first thing,'' Dubcek said in the interview.
   The latest protests began on Jan. 15, when about 5,000 activists
tried to hold a vigil for Palach in Wenceslas Square. Police broke
up the crowd with tear gas and truncheons and arrested 117 people.
   Palach had set himself on fire in the square to protest the
Soviet invasion that led to Dubcek's ouster.
   On Jan. 16, Czechoslovakia's best-known dissident, banned
playwright Vaclav Havel, and 12 other prominent activists were
detained after trying to lay flowers in memory of Palach. They are
still in jail, and fellow activists say it appears they will face
charges that could jail them for up to two or three years.
   Mlada Fronta said Saturday that 280 people were detained Thursday
during the week's worst violence, when riot police charged a crowd
of more than 2,000 and beat several people in Prague.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
