<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     01-22 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leader Denounces Calls For His Ouster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist party chief Stipe Suvar
denounced calls for his ouster and warned that the economically and
ethnically troubled country could fall victim to political
extremism, a published report said Sunday.
   Suvar also predicted frank discussions at a Central Committee
meeting this week of the ruling League of Communists, but implied he
expected to withstand an effort to run him out of office.
   The party chief has been the focus of unprecedented attacks by
Serbian leaders that reflect the hard-line stance of the Serbian
communist party led by Slobodan Milosevic, who is believed to have
presidential aspirations.
   Suvar, president of the executive Presidium, accused ``sections''
of the party, media and various political meetings of being
``maximally concentrated on dismembering the current ... Central
Committee and its Presidium and ... on eventually replacing,
blocking and fully compromising its current president.
   ``The tension in the country has increased and so has the concern
of the great majority (of Yugoslavs) for the fate of socialism in
our country,'' he said in an interview on Zagreb television Saturday
night that was carried by newspapers Sunday.
   Suvar warned that rifts in the country's leadership comprised a
``clash of concepts'' that could lead the country to extremes,
either restoration of a ``bourgeois'' system or ``neo-Stalinism.
   There has been increasing unrest in Yugoslavia where inflation is
hovering at 250 percent, living standards are sinking and the
country is burdened by a $21 billion foreign debt.
   Suvar said he was ``deeply convinced'' that the League of
Communists' Central Committee meeting scheduled for Wednesday would
be marked by ``a completely open discussion ... and we must no
longer play hide and seek.''
   The Central Committee meeting is widely expected to reflect
deepening rifts in the Yugoslav leadership and result in a clash
between liberal factions in the party and a hard-line coalition led
by Milosevic.
   ``We must call matters ... relations ... and persons by their
true name,'' Suvar said in the interview, adding that he was ready
``to fully account for everything before the Central Committee which
elected me to the Presidium, and before the presidium which elected
me (its) president.''
   Suvar has been accused at numerous party meetings in Serbia and
in the republic of Montenegro of allegedly opposing mass street
demonstrations that forced the ouster of the entire Montenegrin
ruling elite. A communist party conference in the province of
Vojvodina also called for his ouster last week.
   The protests were seen in the northern republics of Croatia and
Slovenia as having been orchestrated by Milosevic supporters to
bring Montenegro under tighter political control by Serbia.
   However, Suvar, a Croat, indicated he did not expect the
communist leadership to replace him, saying he hoped to remain party
chief for the remaining six months of his tenure.
   Suvar suggested that people taking part in mass rallies that
forced the resignations of numerous Serbian and Montenegrin leaders
allegedly opposed to Milosevic were being ``led astray ... by
demagogues.
   ``We can depose leaderships,'' he said, but warned, ``such an
atmosphere ... would lead us to disaster.''
   In another development, the Tanjug news agency reported a
communist party meeting in the Croatian town of Zlatar Bistrica on
Saturday demanded that Milosevic, as a member of the Yugoslav
communist Party Presidium, be called to account for
``moral-political responsibility'' over his not reacting to
``unargumented attacks'' on Suvar at the Vojvodina party conference.
   Much of last year's unrest has centered on the province of
Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians form a majority of more than 90
percent. Serbia is the largest republic, and both provinces, Kosovo
and Vojvodina, are part of it but not fully subject to its control.
</TEXT>
