<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     01-22 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Alliance Picks Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition coalition on Sunday
formally selected attorney Guillermo Endara as its candidate in the
May 7 presidential election.
   In a related development, the Panamanian military accused the
United States of harassing Panamanians.
   Endara, 52, pledged to form a ``government of national
reconstruction'' and replace Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, head of
Panama's Defense Forces and country's de facto ruler.
   The opposition alliance also selected Ricardo Arias Calderon, 53,
as candidate for first vice president and Guillermo Ford, 52, as
second vice president.
   Arias Calderon, a former vice presidential candidate, is
president of the Democratic Christian Party. Ford, a businessman, is
a member of the executive committee of the National Liberal
Republican Movement Party.
   Calderon described the May 7 balloting as a ``plebescite'' on
Noriega's rule.
   ``Let's go into the streets to end this regime,'' said Arturo
Vallarino, a delegate from the Republican party. ``We have the
spirit to rebel and not submit.''
   The Civic Crusade and several other small opposition parties took
part in the convention along with the Democratic Christian Party and
the National Liberal Republican Movement.
   Another opposition party,, the Authentic Liberal Party, plans a
nominating convention next week and the seven-party government
coalition will announce its candidate on Feb. 1.
   Meanwhile, Noriega's Defense Forces on Sunday accused U.S. troops
of having ``intensified their campaign of persecution'' against
Panamanians entering areas under U.S. control.
   ``This campaign of persecution includes threats with firearms,
insults, illegal and unnecessary interrogations, arbitrary arrest,
the excessive use of force, cruel and degrading treatment,'' the
Defense Forces said in a press release.
   The statement said the interrogations are conducted by U.S.
military intelligence agents trying to obtain information about
Panama's internal affairs.
   The Defense Forces said U.S. troops have no right to detain
Panamanian citizens and it urged people who are detained to ``remain
calm,'' refuse to sign any documents and demand to see a Panamanian
military policeman.
   U.S. Southern Command spokesman Bill Ormsbee said he would have
no comment Sunday on the Defense Forces statement.
   The Defense Forces said the ``campaign of persecution'' is worst
along the Panama Canal near Southern Command headquarters. The
command has about 13,000 troops guarding the canal, which will be
turned over to Panamanian control in the year 2000.
   Tensions between U.S. and Panamanian troops have been high since
the United States began trying last year to force Noriega to
relinquish power. A U.S. federal grand jury has indicted Noriega on
drug trafficking charges.
</TEXT>
