<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Students     01-22 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Students,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youths Return to Rangoon from Rebel Camp, But Many Fearful Exiles
Stay Behind</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 90 youths returned to the capital
Sunday after an week-long journey from a rebel camp, where they had
fled to excape a military crackdown last year, a student said.
   Maung Pe Win, 23, a law student from Rangoon University, said
about 250 youths remained at the U Thuta camp near the Thai border.
Most wanted to return, he said, but three student leaders dissuaded
them, saying the military would kill those who returned.
   He said about 60 percent of students in the border areas have
become ill and six died at U Thuta camp.
   About 100 set out on foot Jan. 14 from U Thuta, but illness
forced 13 to drop out in villages along the seven-day walk to
Kamamaung in Karen state, Pe Win said. From there, the military
transported the 87 remaining youths, mostly students, to Thaton
camp, about 100 miles east of Rangoon, and then to Rangoon to return
to their homes.
   The U Thuta camp is controlled by the Karen National Union, one
of about a dozen ethnic groups fighting the central government for
greater autonomy. Thousands of youths fled to such camps after the
Sept. 18 military coup led by Gen. Saw Maung.
   About 2,000 have returned home, some by land and others by air
from Thailand.
</TEXT>
