<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Earthquake 1stLd-Writethru   01-22 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Earthquake, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0767,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Hits Northern Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT time conversion in 3rd graf
to 5: 20 p.m., sted a.m.; picks up 4th pvs: A tremor...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake registering 6.1 on the Richter
scale hit northern Japan early Monday, the Central Meteorological
Agency said. Local police said there were no immediate reports of
damage or injuries.
   The agency said the quake's was centered 24 miles below the
seabed off the coast of the city of Kushiro, 556 miles northwest of
Tokyo, on the northernmost main island of Hokkaido.
   The tremor, which occurred at about 7:20 a.m. (5:20 p.m. EST),
registered a 3 on the Japanese scale of 7 in the Hokkaido cities of
Kushiro, Obihiro, Urakawa and Hiroo, the agency said.
   A tremor measuring three on the Japanese scale is described as
``rather strong,'' one that can shake houses and buildings and cause
hanging objects such as electric lamps to swing.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake at its
epicenter, according to ground motion as recorded on seismographs.
An earthquake of 6 on the Richter scale is considered ``severe,'
capable of widespread damage if it hits a populated area.
   The Japanese scale measures the intensity of an earthquake at a
particular location.
</TEXT>
