<FIRST>r a AM-GlazeTrial     01-22 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glaze Trial,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drifter Faces Trial in Slayings of Three Indian Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULA FROKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drifter who said his fascination with
American Indians led him to pose as one is on trial for the killings
of three Indian women.
   Testimony was to start Monday in the trial of Billy Richard
Glaze, 44, who is charged with six counts of first-degree murder in
the mutilation deaths of the women. The trial is expected to last
six to eight weeks.
   Many in Minneapolis' American Indian community say they are
relieved to see the case go to trial.
   ``People are happy that someone has been caught and questioned
and is going on trial for the murders,'' said Frances Fairbanks,
director of the American Indian Center in a neighborhood near
downtown, where the bodies were found.
   ``Hopefully he's the right one,'' said the head of security for
the American Indian Movement's AIM Patrol, who identified himself
only as Bear. The group polices Indian neighborhoods.
   Glaze had pleaded innocent to the charges. He is being held on $2
million bail.
   The victims _ Kathleen Kay Bullman, Angeline Whitebird-Sweet and
Angela Kay Greene _ all were patrons of Franklin Avenue bars, where
police say they believe the women met their killer.
   Their bodies were mutilated and posed in suggestive positions
after their deaths, prompting Minneapolis police homicide head Jack
McCarthy to term the slayer ``a vicious killer'' who was ``making
some kind of a statement.''
   Glaze once told a television reporter that he had claimed to be
an Indian because American Indians fascinated him, and federal
authorities said he used aliases including Jesse Settingcrow and
Jesse Sitting Crow.
   Peter Cahill, Glaze's lawyer, would not discuss the case.
   Assistant Hennepin County Attorney Pete Connors said prosecutors
would not comment.
   A grand jury heard testimony from 50 witnesses over six days last
May and deliberated less than an hour before indicting Glaze on the
murder charges.
</TEXT>
