<FIRST>r i AM-Jamaica     01-22 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jamaica,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seaga, Manley To Meet For Political Peace Parley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LLOYD WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Edward Seaga and
opposition leader Michael Manley plan to meet Monday to discuss
escalating political violence between the governing Jamaica Labor
Party and the People's National Party.
   The two rivals are to meet at the Wyndham Kingston Hotel at 5
p.m., shortly after their respective parties nominate the official
candidates for the Feb. 9 elections.
   The prime minister scheduled the meeting after Manley wrote him a
letter requesting they meet in light of the surge of political
violence within the past week.
   Basil Francis, 58, was killed and Merlina Wright, 49, and Norma
Richards, 39, were shot and wounded Friday during a clash between
rival political bands in Spanish Town, the police said.
   There also have been clashes reported between supporters of
Seaga's Labor party and Manley's People's National Party.
   In his letter, Manley said such confrontations constitute a
breach of an agreement reached in August 1988.
   ``We agreed, for example, that every effort should be made to
ensure that our respective supporters would not be mobilized to
harass, heckle, jeer and, in particular, provoke our opponents at
public meetings and on tours,'' Manley recalled.
   ``I am therefore suggesting that we meet together again very
urgently ... to review what has been taking place, and finalized
more precise methods of closer communication,'' Manley wrote.
   Seaga replied quickly in a letter suggesting that they and their
respective peace committees meet Monday to sign previously
negotiated peace agreements for the constituencies in the Kingston,
St. Andrew and St. Catherine parishes and then discuss the current
situation.
   ``I consider that these proposals would send the right signals
and the talks would be productive, based on the earlier discussions
during this week between the chairmen of the two parties,'' Seaga
said.
   Manley, in his letter, had said the recent incidents of violence
``have given me very great concern,'' and he wondered whether
``deliberate acts of provocation'' were being organized and staged
at the constituency level to discredit the Code of Conduct signed
between the two leaders in August.
   Justice James Kerr, the ombudsman for political matters, proposed
over the weekend that both parties ban political motorcades which,
he said, ``served no purpose other than providing a cover for the
devotees of strife and the promoters of violence to do their
destructive work.''
   Manley said that the People's National Party already has decided
not to hold anymore motorcades.
   However, he said he would tour individual constituencies almost
daily, and his parties' other candidates would be doing the same.
   What was important, he said, was that both sides already had
agreed to provide each other at the national and constituency levels
with their respective itineraries, a procedure which should be
implemented as a matter of routine from now on.
   Seaga wrote that ``several candidates of the Jamaica Labor Party
share my own concern that political violence is once again rearing
its ugly head'' and cited recent incidents in which Labor Party
supporters were attacked in St. Andrew parish.
   The prime minister also spoke of ``the near open warfare now
taking place in the main urban centers of St. Catherine,
particularly Spanish town and Old Harbor, which culminated with the
fire-bombing of the Old Harbor office of the JLP on Friday night.''
</TEXT>
