<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Kidnap     01-22 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Kidnap,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Still No Trace of Former Premier One Week after Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators said Sunday they have no
clues to the disappearance of former Prime Minister Paul Vanden
Boeynants and are increasingly worried about his safety.
   ``More than eight days after his abduction, we are more and more
frightened,'' said Prosecutor Andre Rutten. ``At the moment there is
no change whatsoever in the situation.''
   The previously unknown Socialist Revolutionary Brigade claimed it
abducted Vanden Boeynants only hours after his disappearance Jan. 14
and said at first he would be killed.
   On Tuesday, it demanded about $800,000 in ransom but police have
not heard from the group since, casting doubts whether it kidnapped
Vanden Boeynants.
   Rutten said Sunday a judicial dossier on the 69-year-old
Christian Democratic leader had vanished from the files but was it
was still unclear whether this was linked to his disappearance.
   Vanden Boeynants was given a three-year suspended jail sentence
in 1986 for tax fraud as head of his meatpacking business.
   The dossier has documentation on the relations between Vanden
Boeynants and two former police officials who have long been
investigated for a series of crimes.
   ``We have no elements that can make us think there is a relations
between the disappearance of Vanden Boeynants and the disappearance
of the dossier,'' Rutten said.
   Vanden Boeynants disappeared on the evening of Jan. 14 after
parking his car near his home and police found indications he might
have been kidnapped.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister from 1966 to 1968 and from
late 1978 to early 1979. He was also defense minister for seven
years during the 1970s.
