<FIRST>r i AM-Ireland-Arms     01-22 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ireland-Arms,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Police Uncover Arms Cache</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGFIELD, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish police said they found an Irish
Republican Army arms cache Sunday that included barrels, ammunition
and tripods for powerful Soviet-made machine guns capable of
shooting down helicopters.
   Police said the weapons and ammunition were found in a plastic
container buried underground at a deserted farm at Longfield in
County Monaghan, near the border with Northern Ireland.
   It was the fifth such discovery this year.
   A police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
latest find included a Soviet-made Kalashnikov rifle, more than 900
rounds of ammunition and ammunition boxes and belts.
   He said police also found six machine-gun barrels, tripods and
ammunition for Soviet-made 12.7 mm heavy machine guns. The IRA used
a similar heavy machine gun to shoot down a British Army helicopter
in South Armagh, Northern Ireland, in June.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to oust the British from Northern
Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the
mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
