<FIRST>r i AM-India 1stLd-Writethru   01-22 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0682,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Hindus Hanged In Revenge For Executions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS seven grafs with London demonstration; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists dragged three Hindu men
from their homes and hanged them to avenge the executions of two
Sikhs convicted in the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi, police said Sunday.
   The Saturday night attack in the village of Ahema Khalan, 21
miles south of Amritsar, was the second such incident reported since
Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh were hanged in New Delhi on Jan. 6 for
Mrs. Gandhi's assassination.
   Senior police superintendent Suresh Arora said six or seven Sikhs
entered Gian Chand's home and took him and his brother, Madan Lal.
   Their uncle, Vir Bhan, was taken from a neighboring house, and
all three men were dragged to the village outskirts and hanged from
a tree, Arora said.
   He said a note left near the bodies said the killings were in
retaliation for the executions of Satwant Singh, who was convicted
of assassinating Mrs. Gandhi, and Kehar Singh, who was convicted of
conspiracy in the killing.
   The note bore the name of the Kalistan Commando Force, one of
several extermist groups waging a violent campaign for an
independent Sikh nation, Arora said.
   On Jan. 11, four Hindu brothers were hanged in Bhujiawali, 40
miles north of Amritsar. A note found near their bodies warned that
more people would be hanged because of the government executions.
   Sikh militants, who killed at least 2,440 people in northern
Punjab state last year, have killed more than 140 people so far this
year.
   The radicals have been fighting for a separate nation since 1982,
claiming members of their faith are discriminated against by India's
Hindu majority.
   Sikhs comprise only 2 percent of India's population of 880
million but form a majority in Punjab state. Hindus account for
about 80 percent of the national population.
   The Sikh faith has roots in both Hinduism and Islam.
   In London, meanwhile, about 4,000 Sikhs marched through the city
to protest the executions.
   Men, women and children gathered in Hyde Park before marching
along Oxford Street and Kingsway to Temple subway station near India
House, the office of the Indian high commmmissioner, or ambassador.
   A police cordon separated the marchers from the commission.
   Five Sikh elders carrying swords and scimitars led the
procession. Many marchers wore brightly colored turbans.
   On Sunday, medical student Dapinder Singh, one of the march
organizers, said: ``This procession is the first time that Sikhs
have come together under one banner. There are no more factions, we
are unified now and this is terrifying the Indian government.''
   About 400,000 Sikhs live in Britain.
   There was one brief scuffle between police and a marcher,
followed by a confrontation with more marchers, but an appeal for
calm by the march stewards defused the situation.
</TEXT>
