<HEAD>Iraqis Allowed to Write Letters To The Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Sunday that Iraqis can
now write letters to state-run newspapers to criticize people ``who
commit any action that could be harmful to society.''
   The official radio said Information Minister Latif Nussayif
Jassim was asked by the ruling Revolution Command Council to permit
such complaints.
   The radio said that those under attack would be given a forum in
the same newspaper to respond.
   Iraq's four main state-run dailies previously did not publish
readers' letters.
   A similar council order last week permitted people to write
letters to the newspapers naming government officials who abuse
their authority or violate regulations.
   It said the officials also would be allowed to reply through the
press.
   The moves appeared aimed at making government officials more
accountable and at improving freedom of expression.
