<FIRST>u w AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0722 01-22 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0722,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>New President Attends National Prayer Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 16th graf pvs, bgng: ``He hosted...'' to
reflect call after Super Bowl; picks up 17th graf pvs, bgng: ``Just before...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, taking a pause from celebrative
inauguration events, attended a national worship service Sunday
where he was recognized as the ``symbol of unity.''
   The solemn interfaith ``National Prayer Service'' in the
sanctuary of the ornate Washington Cathedral served as a quiet,
contemplative climax to a frenetic five-day inauguration festival.
   While Bush worshipped with some 3,200 others, top aides appeared
on Sunday television interview shows to discuss the more secular
matters of budget deficits and U.S.-Soviet relations.
   The new president and first lady Barbara Bush kneeled and prayed
silently when they entered the cathedral, and then joined Vice
President Dan Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, in a front pew.
   Presiding over the service was the Rev. John T. Walker,
Episcopalian bishop of Washington, who noted that the Bushes,
Episcopalians themselves, had ``visited with us many times in the
past.'' He said he hoped to see them often, and the Bushes had said
previously that they intended to attend Sunday church services
regularly.
   Walker spoke of ``a nation united in the person of our president.
He is our symbol of unity.''
   The Rev. Peter Gomes, minister of Memorial Church at Harvard
University, who delivered the principal sermon, said, ``We have come
to pray for the reconcilation of the peoples of the nation.''
   Gomes worried aloud about ``the destitute of our American
Calcuttas'' and on behalf of ``the prisoners of the inner city
within a few short blocks of this cathedral and beyond.'' He also
urged compassion for the aged, for AIDS victims and for ``the
prisoners of affluence and indifference.''
   In this he took a page from Bush's inauguration address of
Friday, in which he said, ``My friends, we are not the sum of our
possessions. They are not a measure of our lives.''
   The Bushes and the other worshippers laughed when Gomes cited an
old adage, ``Be careful for what you pray, you might get it.''
   ``The former vice president of the United States prayed doubtless
to become president, and now he has. And now we must all pray with
him and for him,'' Gomes said.
   Bush's oldest son, George Walker Bush, 42, participated in the
service, reading a litany and ending it with, ``God protect our
mother and father.''
   Walker closed the service with the prayer that Bush himself had
used in his inaugural address on Friday: ``Use power to help people.
... There is but one use of power _ and it is to serve people.''
   The Bushes joined the rest of the congregation in singing songs
from the printed program, including ``Faith of Our Fathers,''
``Amazing Grace,'' and Beethoven's ``Ode to Joy.''
   Bush, who surprised top aides and startled White House reporters
with several spur-of-the-moment appearances in public in recent
days, remained for the most part behind the scenes Sunday.
   He hosted an afternoon reception for members of the inauguration
committee and set aside the early evening to join his family in the
White House residence theater to watch the Super Bowl on wide-screen
television.
   After the game, Bush called National Football League Commissioner
Pete Rozelle and invited the victorious San Francisco 49ers to visit
the White House. No date was specified.
   Just before going to church, he appeared briefly on the South
Lawn, where he'd taken grandson George, 12, for a walk. ``It's a
great day,'' exclaimed Bush, who was wearing suitpants and a blue
wind-breaker.
   He seemed ready to relax after attending a series of inauguration
balls Friday, and two more parties on Saturday night. At a youth
rhythm-and-blues party, he got up on the stage and strummed a gift
guitar a few times.
   As Bush prepared for his first full week as president, his chief
of staff, former New Hampshire governor John Sununu, was describing
how Bush wants to consolidate the ``redirection'' of the country
that had begun during Ronald Reagan's eight-year presidency.
   Sununu, interviewed on CBS-TV's ``Face The Nation,'' said that
while Bush wanted to maintain economic prosperity and continue
Reagan's emphasis on a strong defense, he also planned to work hard
on such vexing problems as homelessness, drugs, child care and
education.
   He acknowledged that budget deficit problems would constrain the
chief executive, but said that in the days between now and Feb. 9,
when Bush plans to address a joint session, administration officials
want to emphasize ``our commitment to these issues.''
   Sununu said ``a conservative president can be compassionate.''
   But he refused to be tied down on whether Bush's no-tax pledge
would hold up for the next four years.
   ``I think what George Bush said to the American people was that
we will deal with the deficit, the fundamental issue, without
raising taxes,'' he said. ``We are putting a blueprint to deal with
the deficit that does not require taxes.''
   But when asked whether the Bush promise was intended to be good
for just one year, or four years, the chief of staff said the pledge
should be sound ``as long as the climate of this country is
appropriate for that commitment to stay in place.''
  
</TEXT>
