<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0687 01-22 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Drug Ring Smashed In Iran As New Law Takes Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with addicts and pushers turning
themselves in, some relatives alerting police, heroin prices jump; picks
up 4th graf `The radio...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian authorities smashed a major drug
ring and killed six of its members Sunday, while a tough new
anti-narcotics law caused addicts and pushers to turn themselves in
and heroin prices to soar, reports said.
   In the last few days, Iran has executed 75 people and arrested
more than 1,000 people nationwide in what Iran's official Islamic
Republic News Agency termed ``the biggest crackdown on drug
smuggling in Iran's history.''
   Many addicts and pushers deserted their hideouts and turned
themselves in to avoid arrest, said the reports monitored in
Nicosia. The agency said 50 users were handed over to rehabilitation
centers but did not say what happened to the rest.
   Cafe owners previously tolerant of drug abusers on their premises
were turning them away since the new law calls for prosecuting
anyone who provides a refuge for them, the news agency said. Even
friends and relatives of addicts and pushers were alerting
authorities, it said.
   The anti-drug campaign caused heroin prices to jump four-fold
Sunday, a day after the new anti-drug law went into effect, the
Iranian news agency reported without giving any specific figures.
   In the northern Mazandaran province, three addicts committed
suicide by taking large heroin doses and then electrocuting
themselves, it said.
   The radio said the drug ring smashed Sunday was run by Habib
Naroui, who operated in southeastern Kerman and in
Sistan-Baluchistan.
   The broadcast said six members of his ring were killed in a raid
by agents of the Tehran and Kerman komiteh, the government's main
law enforcement agency. The report did not describe the
confrontation or say how the dealers died. It said 280 pounds of
opium were confiscated.
   In other raids Sunday, a man was arrested in the capital, Tehran,
with 22 pounds of heroin and 44 pounds of opium, the broadcast said.
Two other men were arrested in Kerman, it said.
   The report said an unspecified number of people in another gang
were arrested in the northern Semnan province and 145 pounds of
opium were seized.
   Two other drug smugglers were arrested who operated in the
capital and in central Isfahan province, the radio said. It said
without elaborating that a large sum of money and six vehicles were
confiscated from them.
   The new anti-narcotics law that went into effect Saturday
requires the death penalty for anyone convicted of possessing one
ounce of heroin, codeine or morphine, or smuggling more than 10
pounds of opium or hashish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
