<HEAD>Government Paid 13 Percent of GNP in Internal Debt Interest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government paid the equivalent of
13 percent of Mexico's gross national product in interest alone on
its internal debt in 1988, according to a report by the private
Market Investigation Bureau.
   In contrast, the government paid little more than the equivalent
of 6 percent of GNP to service its $106 billion foreign debt last
year, the bureau said.
   It called for prompt action to reduce the internal debt, the
Excelsior news agency reported.
   Mexico's GNP is estimated at $160 billion; estimated servicing of
the domestic debt last year totaled $20 billion, while foreign debt
payments reached around $9 billion.
   Economists blame heavy government borrowing to service the
domestic debt as a major cause of inflation, which reached 51.7
percent last year.
