<HEAD>New York Times Machinists Ratify Labor Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE with comment from Times; picks up 6th
graf pvs bg'ng, Negotiators reached ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The machinists at The New York Times voted Sunday
to ratify an agreement on a 6-year extension of a labor contract
that expired nearly two years ago, a union official said.
   The pact, retroactive to April 1987, calls for $233.35 weekly in
additional wages and benefits for each worker over six years and
contains language for better job security for the 72 machinists,
said George E. McDonald, president of the Allied Printing Trades
Council, an umbrella group that includes 10 of the 14 unions at the
Times.
   Members of the Eureka Lodge 434 of the International Association
of Machinists voted overwhelmingly to approve the contract,
according to McDonald. However, the exact vote tally and details of
the agreement were not available Sunday, he said.
   ``It's a good contract. I'm delighted that the machinists settled
with The New York Times,'' McDonald said.
   Times spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen said, ``The Times is pleased the
machinists union reached an agreement. This is the last of our
unions to sign a 6-year agreement.''
   Negotiators reached their agreement Thursday, just hours before a
strike deadline.
   The union membership had rejected an earlier tentative settlement
on Jan. 8 and authorized a strike at 12:01 a.m. EST last Friday,
unless a new deal was reached.
   The machinists, who maintain and repair presses and other
equipment, were the last of 14 unions to reach pacts with the Times
covering wages, benefits and job security through March 1993.
   Their contract expired March 31, 1987.
   The contract agreements for the unions are similar, but issues of
job security were different for various unions, and some are to be
subject to further negotiations or arbitration.
