<FIRST>r f AM-IceCreamRecall     01-22 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ice Cream Recall,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Store Recalls Ice Cream Possibly Exposed to Ammonia Gas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A supermarket chain recalled certain
packages of a store-brand ice cream Saturday because of possible
exposure to ammonia gas during manufacture, a spokesman said.
   Stater Brothers Markets recalled its brand of square-pack,
half-gallon packages of ice cream in golden vanilla and chocolate
flavors bearing the code 092289, said spokesman Tom Reingrover.
   ``It's strictly a precautionary thing,'' he said. ``The recall is
on all of that code, however we found very little product affected.''
   The packages did not necessarily end up in all of Stater
Brothers' 101 markets in Southern California but there was no way to
determine which stores actually received the lot, Reingrover said.
   The code is printed on an end flap of the packages. Some of the
ice cream in those packages may be discolored, have an off-flavor
and ammonia odor.
   The ice cream was made for Stater Brothers Markets by Knudsen Co.
but no Knudsen products or other brands were affected, Stater
Brothers said.
   Reingrover said he did not know how many packages were in the
recalled lot.
   Consumers were advised to return the ice cream to the store where
they bought it to receive a refund.
   The ice cream was manufactured in late December and was in the
stores for ``a very short period of time,'' Reingrover said. He did
not know exactly when it was put into the stores.
   The contamination occurred because of a leak of ammonia gas from
the system that freezes the ice cream during the manufacturing
process, he said.
</TEXT>
