<DOCNO> AP890122-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WestCoastVideo Bjt   01-22 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-West Coast Video, Bjt,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Coast Video, Based Far From Hollywood, Is World's Largest Video
Chain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can't get much farther from the West
Coast than northeast Philadelphia.
   But underneath the image of a blazing sun on a bright red sign,
Elliot Stone opened the first West Coast Video stores in the
second-largest city on the East Coast.
   After five years, scores of franchise contracts and the buyout of
struggling Portland, Ore.-based National Video Inc.'s franchise
operations, West Coast Video has grown into the largest video rental
outlet in the world. ``Even from the start, our name had given the
impression that we were a nationally-franchised company,'' said
Stone, the chain's founder and chief executive officer. ``We wanted
a Hollywood image _ flashing lights, tons of glitter.''
   Laden with bright-red carpeting and wallpaper, tracer lights and,
of course, movie posters, the West Coast Video stores have brought a
franchise formula to what started as family-owned operations with
little commitment toward growing nationally.
   ``It's gone big-time now'' and gone beyond the level of stores
that were opened as a hobby, said Steven Apple, executive editor of
Video Insider, a trade magazine.
   ``Every day, mom-and-pop stores are closing. Our stores are
replacing the mom-and-pop operations,'' Stone said.
   Sitting behind his U-shaped desk in his overwhelmingly blue
office _ nearly devoid of red _ Stone is a successful entrepreneur,
but not altogether satisfied.
   Plans for 1989 are to increase growth from three franchises a
week and one company store every 10 days to opening a new outlet
every working day.
   Last year, after the acquisition of National Video for about $3
million in cash and the addition of 455 franchised outlets, West
Coast had $180 million in revenue, according to Sarah Killion,
company spokeswoman. That was up sharply from 1986 revenue of $11
million.
   In its December 1988 issue, Inc. magazine listed West Coast Video
as the fourth-fastest growing privately-owned company in the
country, with sales jumping 22,653 percent between 1983 and 1987.
   As of Jan. 11, there were 650 stores, 455 of which came from
National Video, 195 West Coast Video franchises and 68 company-owned
stores.
   Stone said the company has gone through periods when it grew too
fast for the staff and equipment. But he is confident that with VCRs
in 55 percent of U.S. homes, the rental industry will continue to
grow for another five to 10 years.
   Competition for West Coast, however, may come from convenience
and grocery store chains that set aside a rack or corner for movie
rentals. Such stores can offer movie rentals at a lower rate because
they don't depend on rentals for their income. Also, convenience
stores like 7-Eleven already have stores on street corners across
the country.
   But according to Apple, people prefer to go to a store
specializing in videos by a margin of three to one. He said
customers are attracted by the selection and service provided by a
video store.
   ``I see it very much as an industry that will continue to be
dominated by video specialty stores with growing business in
convenience stores,'' said Stephen Wilson, chairman of Fairfield
Group Inc., a market research firm specializing in the video
business.
   Stone started West Coast Video in September 1983 after he and his
wife couldn't find the movie they were looking for and thought the
clerks were rude.
   ``We saw all these people walking into a retail outlet for one
sole purpose _ to rent a movie,'' Stone said. ``Here they're already
in the store and not coming out with a movie.''
   Several years ago, most video stores kept the tapes behind a
counter and the customer was expected to walk up with a list of
movies and ask the clerk which ones were in stock.
   Stone takes credit for introducing a new system, emulated by
many, that displays an empty box for each copy of a movie in stock.
When the customer picks up the box, he is assured of being able to
rent the movie.
   Many stores will give a customer a free day's rental if the movie
for a displayed box is not in stock.
   Occasionally, with franchisees who have taken a second mortgage
on their house or invested their life savings in the store, it is
difficult to convince them that giving away $2 worth of rentals will
pay off if the customer comes back.
   At $35,000, West Coast Video's franchise fee is $6,000 higher
than any other video franchiser, according to the Franchise
Handbook, published by Enterprise Magazines Inc. of Milwaukee, Wisc.
Between $175,000 and $250,000 in capital is required to start a West
Coast Video store.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890122-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Suburban-Pilots     01-22 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suburban-Pilots,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suburban Pilots Reject Contract Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>READING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots for Suburban Airlines, a regional
commuter service based in Reading, moved a step closer to a strike
when they rejected the company's latest contract offer.
   Bill Welch, a spokesman for Council 78 of the Air Line Pilots
Association, said union pilots voted almost unanimously against
ratifying a contract proposal offered by the airline. He declined to
say how many ballots were cast, but said 97 percent were against
ratification.
   ``We either go back into mediation or we could go on strike
within 30 to 60 days,'' Welch said Saturday night after the ballots
were counted in the Holiday Inn.
   Suburban, a wholly-owned subsidiary of USAir Group Inc., flies to
Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Washington and several other Eastern
cities. It services the Allentown-Bethlehem-Easton Airport as well
as Reading and Lancaster, all in Pennsylvania.
   The Reading-based Council 78, which is the bargaining agent for
90 pilots, has been negotiating with Suburban for 15 months. A
federal mediator was brought into the talks about five months ago.
   John Mazor, a spokesman in Washington, D.C., for the Air Line
Pilots Association, said the mediator would have to determine that a
stalemate exists and both sides would have to refuse to enter
arbitration before the pilots could strike.
   Welch declined to discuss the details of Suburban's offer, but
indicated that wages and scheduling were among the major obstacles.
   Under the existing contract, Welch said, a newly hired co-pilot
would start at $1,050 a month and a first-year captain earns $1,920
a month. The wages, he said, are based on 80 hours of flying time a
month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
