<DOCNO> AP890122-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Zambia-IMF     01-22 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zambia-IMF,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zambia Resumes Ties with IMF</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kenneth Kaunda said his Southern
African nation accepted an offer by the International Monetary Fund
to resume an economic restructuring program in Zambia.
   In the text of an interview with U.S. reporters issued Sunday,
Kaunda said an accord with the IMF followed what he described as the
fund's ``flexible stance toward needy countries''.
   Speaking with Jane Perlez of The New York Times and Richard
Bonner of New Yorker magazine, Kaunda said the IMF will assist with
homespun economic reforms adopted by his government since he severed
ties with the fund in May 1987.
   ``They made soundings that they want to come back and we said:
`Yes, we are ready,''' Kaunda told the reporters. ``This should be
on our own terms and they (the IMF) should only come here to help us
do what we are already doing,'' he said.
   Several senior officials of the IMF and the World Bank visited
Zambia in recent months to negotiate resumed loan assistance.
   Last year, the Zambian government cut state subsidies on some
essential commodities and removed price controls on some items to
prepare the way for a rapprochement with the IMF.
   When Zambia cut its ties with the IMF in 1987 the government said
the fund's economic austerity program was too harsh.
   That program called for a massive devaluation of the Zambian
currency and the removal of subsidies on essential goods and corn
meal, the staple food.
   Government troops shot dead 15 civilians in food riots in late
1986 after the government slashed its subsidy on corn meal in line
with IMF demands.
</TEXT>
