<FILEID>AP-NR-01-22-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Candy     01-22 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Candy,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owner of Mexican Candy Company Denies LSD Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the candy company Dulces Anahuac
SA denied allegations that LSD-laced decals were distributed in its
candy packages, the government news agency Notimex reported.
   Ricardo Menendez said laboratory analysis conducted by the
federal Health Department and Attorney General's Office failed to
turn up any foreign substance on the decals, Notimex said.
   Last Friday, the National Association of Private Schools said it
had asked the government to investigate the source of LSD on the
decals, which transfer a tattoo-like cartoon onto the skin.
   The decals bear the words ``Made in Spain'' in English and say in
Spanish they were manufactured for Dulces Anahuac SA. Designed to
appeal to young buyers, the decals began showing up recently in the
Mexico City suburb of Ecatepec, Association President Alfredo Villar
said Friday.
   Villar said chemical tests revealed the decals contained several
hallucinogenic substances, including LSD, that can be absorbed
through the skin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
